President Barack Obama has proclaimed October 2014 as National Arts and Humanities Month in the United States. In his proclamation, he highlights the importance of the arts and humanities in enhancing the character of the nation. He emphasizes how these forms of expression bring joy, awe, and sorrow, and contribute to the fabric of society. The President also recognizes the creative spirit and vision of the American people, as well as the role of the arts and humanities in telling the country's story and broadening understanding of the world. He emphasizes the need to cultivate the talents of young people and ensure their access to the arts, as they are critical to the nation's growth and prosperity. The proclamation calls upon the people of the United States to celebrate National Arts and Humanities Month with appropriate ceremonies, activities, and programs.